<subSubSection id="4FFC65060B69165878E8FB382420FAF4" pageId="25" pageNumber="130" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="0759368D0B69165878E8FB382420FAF4" blockId="25.[136,1452,1202,1985]" pageId="25" pageNumber="130">
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B69165878E8FB3826D5FABD" bold="true" box="[189,399,1274,1300]" pageId="25" pageNumber="130">Taxonomic notes:</emphasis>
—The species belongs to section 
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B6916587B5CFB3824DBFABD" box="[777,897,1274,1300]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="130">Nelavagae</emphasis>
and is characterized by the presence of muticous or submuticous mericarps, stems with glandular trichomes and with long simple trichomes, and by decumbent or scandent habit (
<figureCitation id="9FDD2A080B691658796DFA8026BCFAF5" box="[312,486,1346,1372]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="23.[136,229,1993,2015]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,190,1968]" captionTargetId="figure-17@23.[164,1423,190,1968]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 12. A–E. Sida urens. A. Flower. B. Adaxial surface of leaf. C. Branch with flowers and flowers buds. D. Schizocarp. E. Branch with mature schizocarps. F–J. Sida viarum. F. Flower. G. Adaxial surface of leaf. H. Abaxial surface of leaf. I. Branch. J. Immature schizocarps and leaves. Photographs by Martin Grings." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415513" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415513/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="130">Figures 12A–E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="9FDD2A080B69165879A7FA80257FFAF5" box="[498,549,1346,1372]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="26.[136,229,1957,1979]" captionTargetBox="[196,1391,245,1933]" captionTargetId="figure-54@26.[196,1391,245,1933]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 14. Mericarps. A. Sida anomala. B. Sida confusa. C. Sida farroupilhensis. D. Sida glaziovii. E. Sida cerradoensis. F. Sida cordifolia. G. Sida dubia. H. Sida linifolia. I. Sida lonchitis. J. Sida nemorensis. K. Sida paradoxa. L. Sida planicaulis. M. Sida potentilloides.N. Sida reitzii. O. Sida regnellii. P. Sida rhombifolia.Q. Sida riedelii. R. Sida rubifolia.S. Sida spinosa.T. Sida tuberculata. U. Sida urens. V. Sida viarum. Photographs by Martin Grings." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415519" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415519/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="130">14U</figureCitation>
; 
<tableCitation id="4A6403360B6916587A65FA8025DBFAF5" box="[560,641,1346,1372]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,224,340,364]" captionTargetBox="[144,1440,425,1289]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="TABLE 1. Sections of Sida with species occurring in Rio Grande do Sul state, and their diagnostic features, according to Fryxell (1985) and Krapovickas (2003)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/539966050B72164378DDFE962568FE39" pageId="25" pageNumber="130" tableUuid="539966050B72164378DDFE962568FE39">Table 1</tableCitation>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="63774B7C0B6916587ACEFA802434FAF4" author="Krapovickas, A." box="[667,878,1346,1373]" pageId="25" pageNumber="130" pagination="5 - 45" refId="ref19451" refString="Krapovickas, A. (2006) Las especies argentinas y de paises vecinos de Sida secc. Nelavaga (Malvaceae, Malveae). Bonplandia 15: 5 - 45. https: // doi. org / 10.30972 / bon. 151 - 289" type="journal article" year="2006">Krapovickas 2006</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4FFC65060B69165878E8FAA42416F9F1" pageId="25" pageNumber="130" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="0759368D0B69165878E8FAA42416F9F1" blockId="25.[136,1452,1202,1985]" pageId="25" pageNumber="130">
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B69165878E8FAA4258FFA29" bold="true" box="[189,725,1382,1408]" pageId="25" pageNumber="130">Distribution, habitat and conservation status:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName id="C0E64D0E0B6916587AA4FAA4243FFA29" authorityName="Linnaeus (1759:" authorityYear="1145" box="[753,869,1382,1408]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="25" pageNumber="130" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="urens">
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B6916587AA4FAA4243FFA29" box="[753,869,1382,1408]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="130">Sida urens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a wide distribution, and occurs in tropical Africa, the Caribbean, and tropical America, from southern Florida and 
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B6916587B09FA4824E8FA0D" box="[860,946,1418,1444]" name="Mexico" pageId="25" pageNumber="130">Mexico</collectingCountry>
to northern 
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B6916587C69FA4823F1FA0D" box="[1084,1195,1418,1444]" name="Argentina" pageId="25" pageNumber="130">Argentina</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B6916587CB6FA482270FA0D" box="[1251,1322,1418,1444]" name="Brazil" pageId="25" pageNumber="130">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, where it is found in all regions, but not in all states (
<bibRefCitation id="63774B7C0B6916587A07FA6C247EFA61" author="Krapovickas, A." box="[594,804,1454,1480]" pageId="25" pageNumber="130" pagination="5 - 45" refId="ref19451" refString="Krapovickas, A. (2006) Las especies argentinas y de paises vecinos de Sida secc. Nelavaga (Malvaceae, Malveae). Bonplandia 15: 5 - 45. https: // doi. org / 10.30972 / bon. 151 - 289" type="journal article" year="2006">Krapovickas 2006</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="63774B7C0B6916587B7AFA6C2354FA61" author="Brandao, J. L. &amp; Baracho, G. S. &amp; De Sales, M. F. &amp; Filho, M. P. V." box="[815,1038,1454,1480]" pageId="25" pageNumber="130" pagination="205 - 227" refId="ref18144" refString="Brandao, J. L., Baracho, G. S., De Sales, M. F. &amp; Filho, M. P. V. (2017) Synopsis of Sida (Malvaceae, Malvoideae, Malveae) in the state of Pernambuco, Brazil. Phytotaxa 307 (3): 205 - 227. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / phytotaxa. 307.3.5" type="journal article" year="2017">
Brandão 
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B6916587BC1FA6D2497FA61" box="[916,973,1454,1480]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="130">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="63774B7C0B6916587C4CFA6C23F0FA61" author="Bovini, M. G." box="[1049,1194,1454,1480]" pageId="25" pageNumber="130" refId="ref18092" refString="Bovini, M. G. (2020) Sida in Lista de Especies da Flora do Brasil. Jardim Botanico do Rio de Janeiro. Available from: http: // floradobrasil. jbrj. gov. br / jabot / floradobrasil / FB 9206 (accessed 7 July 2020)" type="url" year="2020">Bovini 2020</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingRegion id="C522F86F0B6916587C8FFA6C22F1FA61" box="[1242,1451,1454,1480]" country="Brazil" name="Rio Grande do Sul" pageId="25" pageNumber="130">Rio Grande do Sul</collectingRegion>
the species occurs in 
<taxonomicName id="C0E64D0E0B691658792AFA102683FA45" box="[383,473,1490,1516]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Aristida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="25" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Aristida</taxonomicName>
grassland, Park grassland, Inland subtropical grassland, Coastal grassland, Araucaria Forest, Coastal subtropical Forest and in Tropical Forest, in ruderal environments and anthropized grasslands (
<figureCitation id="9FDD2A080B6916587D35FA3427FDF99D" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="24.[136,229,1957,1979]" captionTargetBox="[266,1345,253,1884]" captionTargetId="figure-25@24.[204,1384,190,1933]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 13. Distribution map of Sida urens and S. viarum in Rio Grande do Sul state, Brazil." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415517" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415517/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="130">Figure 13</figureCitation>
). The species is here considered Least Concern (LC) because it has large EOO and AOO, since it is a frequent and often ruderal species and is present in more than one continent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
